Subject: CLO:0000001
Value: A 'cell line cell' is a part of a cell line established through the passaging/selection of a primary cultured cells or the experimental modification of an existing cell line. New types of cell line cells are established after sufficient passaging of a primary culture to establish a stable and homogenous population that qualifies as a line (typically 1-20 passages), or following some spontaneous or experimental modification that confers novel characteristics to an existing line. A cell line cell typically has mutations of five or more genes compared to the original cell that derives the cell line cell. Some gene mutations may turn on some oncogenes.  Cell line cells can be in active culture, stored in a quiescent state for future use (e.g. frozen in liquid nitrogen), or applied in experimental procedures.

Subject: CLO:0000023
Value: an immortal cell line cell that is generated by fusing two different types of cells. One of the parent cells is typically a cancer cell.

Subject: CLO:0000169
Value: The production of monoclonal antibodies using the hybridoma technology was invented by Cesar Milstein and Georges J. F. Köhler in 1975. They shared the Nobel Prize of 1984 for Medicine and Physiology with Niels Kaj Jerne, who made other contributions to immunology.

Subject: CLO:0000170
Value: a function of a cell that can be passaged in culture medium without death or genetic change.

Subject: CLO:0000171
Value: cell line lineage is a history of the development of a cell line. The cell line lineage may include the original cell type from a tissue and organism that derives the cell line cell. It may also include the cell line passage and cell culturing information.
